 Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Wales","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Wales near Sheffield (South Yorkshire). The placename means ‘The Welshmen’ and denoted a settlement of Brittonic speakers living on the boundary between the Anglo-Saxon kingdoms of Northumbria and Mercia (from Old English <i>wēalas</i>, <i>walas</i>, plural of <i>walh</i>, <i>wealh</i>, originally meaning ‘Roman citizen’ and referring to the native British population, but in Old English this term later came to mean ‘serf, unfree person, foreigner’ or ‘Welshman’). See also   Wallis  .","habitational name from Wales, the country named from Old English <i>wēalas</i> ‘foreigners’ (especially those speaking Celtic or Romance languages). This meaning of the surname is quite rare."],"variants":[{"name":"Wailes","meanings":["English: variant of   Wales  ."]},{"name":"Wallis","meanings":["Scottish and English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>Waleis</i>, <i>Walais</i> ‘Welshman’, also sometimes ‘Breton’ (from Old English <i>wēalas</i>, <i>walas</i>, plural of <i>walh</i>, <i>wealh</i>, originally meaning a ‘Roman citizen’ and referring to the native British population, but in Old English this term later came to mean ‘serf, unfree person, foreigner’ or ‘Welshman’). In western and central England the medieval reference is clearly to Welshmen. In Norfolk and Lincolnshire, the reference was probably to Bretons, many of whom settled in the eastern counties after the Conquest. Compare   Welsh  ,   Walsh  . The idea that the Scottish surname refers to the Welsh-speaking Britons of Strathclyde is erroneous."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Tudwal ap Einudd of Wales Gwynedd was born in 1031, in Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Einudd ab Aelan, was 1 and his mother, Queen Einudd Ap Aelan, was 22. He had at least 2 sons with Einudd of Wales Gwynedd. He died in 1073, in Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1031–1073":"1031–1073","–1071":"–1071","1035–Female":"1035–Surnud","1070–1128":"1070–1128","1030–1070":"1030–1070","1010–1030":"1010–1030","1128":"1128","1035":"1035","1010":"1010","1031":"1031","1030":"1030","1073":"1073","1071":"1071","1070":"1070","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Gwynedd, Wales":"Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Picardie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1031–1073":"1031–1073","–1071":"–1071","1035–Female":"1035–Kuollut","1070–1128":"1070–1128","1030–1070":"1030–1070","1010–1030":"1010–1030","1128":"1128","1035":"1035","1010":"1010","1031":"1031","1030":"1030","1073":"1073","1071":"1071","1070":"1070","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wales":"Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Gwynedd, Wales":"Gwynedd, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Picardie, Ranska"},"fr":{"1031–1073":"1031–1073","–1071":"–1071","1035–Female":"1035–Décédée","1070–1128":"1070–1128","1030–1070":"1030–1070","1010–1030":"1010–1030","1128":"1128","1035":"1035","1010":"1010","1031":"1031","1030":"1030","1073":"1073","1071":"1071","1070":"1070","Wales, United Kingdom":"Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Wales":"Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Gwynedd, Wales":"Gwynedd, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Picardie, France","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Tudwal a